7.1.1 - W11SR04: Reputational Damage and Regulatory Scrutiny
ISM controls:
•	0013; 0015 (Relating to continuous security monitoring and reporting to chief information security officers).
•	0031; 0032 (Relating to the maintenance of an accurate system security plan and security assessment report).
Current Risk There is a risk that a significant cyber incident or a perceived failure to comply with mandatory government security policies (such as the Essential Eight or the PSPF) during the Windows 11 rollout could cause substantial harm to the Department's reputation. Such a failure could lead to intrusive external audits, public criticism, or the requirement to appear before Senate hearings to justify security posturing and investment decisions.
Risk Assessment:
Risk Likelihood	x	Risk Consequence	=	Risk Rating
POSSIBLE	x	MAJOR	=	HIGH
Export to Sheets
Recommendations:
•	Rigorous Governance Framework: Establish a formal project governance board to oversee the migration, ensuring all security milestones are transparently documented and signed off by the Relevant Authority.
•	Proactive Stakeholder Engagement: Maintain regular briefing cycles with departmental leadership and relevant central agencies to communicate progress and proactively manage expectations regarding compliance.
•	Independent Security Assessments: Commission regular, independent IRAP assessments throughout the deployment phases to provide external validation of the security controls and compliance status.
- Treatment #1
•	Develop a comprehensive communications and incident response plan specifically tailored to address public and parliamentary scrutiny following a security event.
•	Implement a continuous compliance monitoring toolset to provide real-time reporting against the ISM and Essential Eight maturity levels.
•	Maintain an evidence-based repository of all security design decisions and risk acceptances to ensure defensibility during external audits or inquiries.
Residual risk outcome if recommendation is implemented. By implementing robust governance, independent validation, and proactive reporting, the Department can demonstrate "due diligence" in its security approach. While the consequence of a public inquiry remains "Major," the likelihood of such an event occurring due to negligence or lack of oversight is reduced to "Unlikely," as the Department will have a defensible and transparent security posture.
